## Configuration Customization

### Modifying values.yaml

You can customize the deployment by editing `values.yaml` before installation:

```yaml
# Example: Enable additional features
nvIPAM:
  deploy: true
  config:
    enableWebhook: true

# Example: Change OFED version
ofedDriver:
  version: "24.01-0.3.3.1"
```

### Node Selection

To deploy Network Operator components on specific nodes, add node selectors:

```yaml
nodeAffinity:
  requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution:
    nodeSelectorTerms:
    - matchExpressions:
      - key: node-role.kubernetes.io/worker
        operator: In
        values:
        - "true"
```

## Troubleshooting

### Pods Not Starting

Check pod status and events:

```bash
kubectl get pods -n {{ .Helm.Namespace }}
kubectl describe pod <pod-name> -n {{ .Helm.Namespace }}
```

### OFED Driver Issues

If OFED driver pods fail to start:

```bash
# Check driver container logs
kubectl logs -n {{ .Helm.Namespace }} -l app=mofed-driver -c mofed-container

# Verify kernel compatibility
kubectl get nodes -o wide
```

### RDMA Device Not Found

Verify NICs are properly detected:

```bash
# On the node, check lspci
lspci | grep Mellanox

# Check device plugin configuration
kubectl get cm -n {{ .Helm.Namespace }} rdma-devices -o yaml
```

### Network Policy Issues

Check NicClusterPolicy status:

```bash
kubectl get nicclusterpolicy -n {{ .Helm.Namespace }} -o yaml
kubectl describe nicclusterpolicy -n {{ .Helm.Namespace }}
```

## Uninstallation

To remove Network Operator from your cluster:

```bash
# Using the uninstall script (recommended)
chmod +x scripts/uninstall.sh
./scripts/uninstall.sh

# Or manually
kubectl delete nicclusterpolicy --all -n {{ .Helm.Namespace }}
helm uninstall network-operator -n {{ .Helm.Namespace }}
kubectl delete namespace {{ .Helm.Namespace }}
```

**Warning:** Uninstalling Network Operator will remove all network configurations and may disrupt running workloads using RDMA or SR-IOV devices.

